Assignment 04 – Exploring Spiking Neurons with Wolfram Language
Course: ITAI 4374 – Neuroscience as a Model for AI
Student: Orhan Gumus
Semester: Spring 2026

The Problem I Was Trying to Solve
This assignment challenged me to implement and explore the Leaky Integrate-and-Fire (LIF) neuron model — one of the most widely used computational models of biological neurons — using Wolfram Language. The goal was to move from conceptual understanding of spiking neurons to hands-on numerical simulation, interactive exploration, and analysis of how neurons encode information.

My Approach
The assignment was structured across five parts:
Part A – Solving the LIF Equation with NDSolve
I defined the core LIF differential equation, set biologically realistic parameters (membrane time constant τ = 20ms, resting potential Vrest = -70mV, threshold Vthresh = -55mV, reset potential Vreset = -75mV), and applied a step current input (18 nA from t = 0.05s to t = 0.4s). I used Wolfram's NDSolve with WhenEvent to detect threshold crossings and reset the membrane potential, simulating spike generation.
Part B – Interactive Manipulate Dashboard
I built an interactive dashboard using Manipulate[] with real-time sliders for threshold, time constant, and input current. This allowed direct exploration of how each parameter affects firing behavior. Key findings: the rheobase (minimum current to elicit firing) is approximately 14 nA, and the neuron stops firing when the threshold is raised above approximately -48 mV.
Part C – f–I Curve Analysis
I swept input current from 0 to 35 nA and plotted the resulting spike counts, generating the frequency-current (f–I) curve. The curve is nonlinear at low currents near threshold, approximately linear in the mid-range, and shows no saturation in this simplified model (which lacks refractory dynamics).
Part D – Encoding a Sine Wave
I drove the LIF neuron with a sinusoidal input current (15 + 12·sin(2π·5·t) nA) over 1 second and observed how the spike train encodes the amplitude of the oscillating input. This demonstrated rate coding: higher current → more spikes per unit time, preserving amplitude information while losing precise waveform shape.
Part E – Experiments
I completed three additional experiments:

Threshold Sweep (-65 to -45 mV): spike count decreases monotonically as threshold rises
Time Constant Comparison: τ = 0.010s produces sharp, frequent spikes; τ = 0.050s produces smoother voltage traces with fewer spikes, matching biological integration behavior
Noisy Input: added uniform random noise to the input current to simulate realistic in-vivo conditions


Results and What They Mean
Threshold behavior confirmed that neurons function as biological decision-makers — they fire only when input exceeds a critical level, implementing a form of nonlinear thresholding that is fundamental to neural computation.
The f–I curve captured the graded response of a neuron to increasing stimulus intensity. The nonlinear onset near rheobase and approximately linear mid-range reflect the kind of stimulus encoding observed in real sensory neurons.
Time constant effects demonstrated the integration-vs.-speed tradeoff: neurons with short τ respond quickly to inputs but are more sensitive to noise; neurons with long τ integrate inputs over time, smoothing variability but responding more slowly to changes.
Rate coding analysis showed that while a spike train can preserve amplitude information from a time-varying input, the precise waveform shape is lost. This supports rate coding as one mechanism of neural information encoding, while also hinting at the limitations of simplified LIF models — real neurons also use timing-based (temporal) coding.
Model strengths and limitations: The LIF model successfully captures membrane integration, threshold-triggered spiking, and reset dynamics. However, it omits dendritic computation, ion channel diversity, spike-frequency adaptation, and refractory periods — all of which shape real neuron behavior. Future work with Hodgkin-Huxley or adaptive exponential IF models would capture these richer dynamics.
The interactive Manipulate[] dashboard was particularly valuable: it transformed abstract differential equations into an intuitive, explorable system and revealed the strong nonlinear sensitivity of firing to small parameter changes — reinforcing the view of neurons as biological decision units rather than linear filters.

